<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WRITTEN EVIDENCE SUBMITTED BY THE WOMEN’S REFUGEE COMMISSION</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">``</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DIS 55</span></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Written evidence submitted by the Women’s Refugee Commission</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Executive Summary</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Women’s Refugee Commission’s (WRC) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seeks to advance the rights and dignity of persons with disabilities affected by crisis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and conflict, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advocacy, research and capacity development initiatives to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support disability-inclusive refugee policy and practice at international and country l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The WRC commends the UK Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Department for International Development (DFID) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its commitment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to persons with disabilities affected by crisis and conflict, most notably </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recent support to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Syrian refugees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with disabilities in Jordan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, as well a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s wider commitments to advancing the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (CRPD) through support to partner governments and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">capacity building </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disabled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> people’s organizations (DPOs) in developing countries.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Recommendations to the Intern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ational Development Committee to further advance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability inclusion across the wider humanitarian sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">(i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Expand understanding of ‘vulnerability’ in the humanitarian sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by supporting systematic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reviews of available literature;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> conducting eva</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">luations of prioritized and targeted assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, identifying </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advantages and disadvantages of different methodologies in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a variety of humanitarian</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contexts;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and  promoting sharing and learning about these different methodologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> across</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the humanitarian sect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or.</span></p><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">(ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Advocate for globally endorsed evidence-based guidelines and standards on disability inclusion within the humanitarian system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">which will in turn support more sustainable plans for capacity development and human resourcing within humanitarian assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> structures. </span></h3><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">(iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Fund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> technical support on disability inclusion in humanitarian action</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> agencies with technical expertise in disability inclusion in humanitarian action to expand their human resource capacity in this field</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">.</span></h3><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none">(iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Integrate crisis and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">conflict issues into disability inclusive development partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">, especially with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">partner governments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">DPOs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">to promote realization of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">CRPD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> for displaced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> persons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">and in turn strengthen the linkages between both development and humanitarian progra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">mming.</span></h3><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Introduction</span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Women’s Refugee Commission’s (WRC) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mission is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to improve the lives and protect the rights of women, children and youth displaced by conflict and crisis, by making humanitarian practice effective, protective and responsive to the n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eeds and capacities of the affected populations, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ensuring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that these communit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies inform and drive solutions. The WRC Disability Program seeks to advance the rights and dignity of persons with disabilities affected by crisis and conflict, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advoca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cy, research and capacity development initiatives to support disability-inclusive refugee policy and practice at international and country levels.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Towards this goal, the WRC conducted a study on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Disabilities among Refugee and Conflict-Affected Populations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in 2008</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which identified that persons with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> disabilities have difficulty accessing humanitarian assistance programs, due to a variety of societal, environmental and communication barriers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Based on these findings, WRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">published a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Resource Kit for Fieldwo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rkers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, providing practical strategies to promote access and inclusion for person with disabilities.</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Over the last two years, the WRC has been partnering with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) on the global roll out of its guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Working with Persons with Disabilities in Forced Displacement,</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> conducting field assessments and providing technical support and training to UNHCR country offices, their implementing partners and disability organizations. WRC also has a current partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hip project with International Rescue Committee (IRC) to pilot actions and build the evidence base on effective strategies for disability inclusion in GBV programs in humanitarian settin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gs.</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[4]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the course of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">providing t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">echnical support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on disability inclus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to humanitarian actors, the WRC has consulted with over 1100 persons affected by crisis and conflict, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refugees and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">internally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">displaced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> persons with disabilities and their care-givers, and engaged </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over 400 humanitarian actors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> through int</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">erviews and participatory workshops</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in India (New Delhi), Uganda, Bangladesh, Ethiopia, Thailand, Nepal, Philippines (Mindanao), Lebanon, Jordan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Burundi and Russia (Grozny).</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WRC makes this written submission to the International Development Commi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ttee to p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rovide information and recommendations on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the key humanitarian issues </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">being investigated as part </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Inquiry into Disability and Development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[5]</a></li></ol><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Findings</span></h2><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">During the course of the WRC’s work on disability inclusion, we have identified some positive practices to promote access and inclusion of persons with disabilities in humanitarian programs, as well as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">critical gaps to advancing inclusion more globally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> across the humanitarian system.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Positive practices to promote access and inclusion in humanitarian programs</span></h3><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The WRC has found the following practices useful in supporting humanitarian organizations to strengthen access and inclusion of persons with disabi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lities in their programs.</span></li></ol><h4 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Context-specific action planning</span></h4><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A variety of guidelines on disability inclusion are available for humanitarian actors.</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These guidelines are largely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">principle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and require field actors to define more detailed action plans wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ich are specific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> programs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contexts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and priority needs or gaps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Over the last</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> two years, the WRC has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">conducted workshops </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UNHCR country offices, partner organizations and host country disability organizations, supporting them to apply existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">guidance on disability inclusion in their given context</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and specific sectors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. In some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">settings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, workshops are adapted to focus on a specific sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or for a given context</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">workshops in Nepal were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">focused on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Disability Inclusion in Gender-Based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Violence Programming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; and o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ne-day disability awareness sessions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were conducted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with local government units</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in Mindanao, Philippines.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All workshops utilize</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> participatory methodologies to promote sharing of knowledge and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">facilitate action planning to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ate guidance into tangible actions at field levels.</span></li></ol><h4 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Bridging the gap between persons with disabilities and humanitarian actors</span></h4><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the course of our work, the WRC has prioritized the central role of persons with di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sabilities in our own activities and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ovision of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">technical support to humanitarian actors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Most notably, persons with disabilities involved in consultations and groups discussions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">asked to appoint representatives to share their protection concerns an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d suggestions for change in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">workshop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">th humanitarian actors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has helped to bridge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the gap between persons with disabilities and decision-makers in different contexts. It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also highlighted their skills and capacities, and potential to contribute to programs and activities like</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> other community members, in some cases facilitating attitudinal change and inclusion in wider community activities.</span></li></ol><h4 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Strengthening </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">individual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> case management</span></h4><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:8.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Persons with disabilities consulted in WRC’s work are facing protection risks as a result of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">multiple and complex un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">met needs, which cross both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">medical and social dimensions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In many contexts, however, there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a tendency to refer the vast majority of per</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sons with disabilities to service providers for health, rehabilitation and provision of aids </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and devices, some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">times failing to recognize other factors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which increase their risk to violence, abuse and exploitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. These factors might include children being out of school, living in substandard shelter, being single parents or care-givers, and sing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">le women with d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">isa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bilities – all of which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">require a more comprehensive and holistic protection assessment and referral to a variety of other non-health-related services.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The WRC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognized that individual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> case management provides a critical entry point</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strengthening assessment of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> protectio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n risks experienced by persons with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can facilitate a more holistic, timely and coordinated response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to persons with specific, co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mplex </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> multiple needs. Individual case management may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">serv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a guide to prioritized service delivery in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resource limited settings. As such, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WRC developed and delivered training in partnership with UNHCR on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Individual Case Management – Identifying and Responding to the Needs of Persons with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for case managers currently engaged in the Syrian refugee response in Lebanon.</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[7]</a></li></ol><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Critical gaps in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">advancing disability inclusion in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> humanitarian </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">action</span></h3><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.93pt; padding-left:3.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite the positive out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">comes of the approaches described </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">abo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve, there are some critical gaps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in advanci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and institutionalizing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability inclusion across the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">humanitarian sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><h4 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Understanding and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">responding to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">vulnerability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> affected populations</span></h4><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Historically, the humanitarian sector has categorized certain groups of people as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the most</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vulnerable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">crisis-affected </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">population</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">umanitarian actors are increasingly aware tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t persons with disabilities are vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to protection risks in humanitarian settings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and consider them as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">one of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> vulnerable groups to identify and reach wit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h services. There is, however, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a significant gap in identifying and responding to the multiple and intersecting factors which make</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> one person more vulnerable and /</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or more resilient than another in humanitarian contexts.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sphere Guidelines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> describe tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">categorizing or labeling a large and diverse group of people, such as persons with disabilities, as ‘vulnerable’ can “lead to fragmented and ineffective interventions, which ignore overlapping vulnerabilities and the changing nature of vulnerabilities ov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er time, even during one specific crisis.”</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Other authors have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">suggested that such an approach can result in “unsophisticated aid targeting”,</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reaching instead the “better-than-average” among that targeted group, rather than the individuals who are most in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> need.</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The WRC has recognized this challenge in humanitarian contexts which are changing rapidly, or where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there are significant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> resource limitations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, such as in the Syrian</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> refugee response in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lebanon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[11]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Persons with disabilities are a diverse group with varying needs and capacities, and identifying the most at risk, as well as the factors which might contribute to the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ir vulnerability and resilience, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">requires a more sophisticated approach.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Persons with dis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">abilities in crisis and conflict affected populations can be both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vulnerable and resilient – dependent on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the place, time, event, shocks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and resources. As such, it may be more appropriate to view the vulnerability of individuals as a continuum based on a v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ariety of factors, such as access to resources, existing assets, and the strength of social networks – rather than based on their membership to a singular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but extremely diverse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> group.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This gap is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">relevant to persons with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but also to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> other groups perceived as ‘vulnerable’ in an emergency. The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> humanitari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an sector at large</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> experiences</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> challenges in understanding and responding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the multiple factors which contribute to vulnerability, as well as resilience, in crisis affected population</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Humanitarian actors require additional tools and resources to effectively and efficiently define vulnerability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in emergency and large scale crisis settings, which are based on variables of vulnerability and resilience, rather than disability features.</span></li></ol><h4 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">lobally endorsed evidence-based guidelines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> on disability inclusion in humanitarian action</span></h4><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To date there are no globally endorsed standards or guidelines relating to persons with disabilities and disability inclusion as a cross cutting issue in humanitarian</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> response. As a result, disability inclusion in the humanitarian sector remains largely driven by disability-specific organizations, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not adequately resourced, both technically and financially, within the wider humanitarian system. The vast majority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of existing guidelines on disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inclusion are largely principle-based, have not been evaluated for effectiveness in the field, and there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> still significant gap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in documented examples of implementation in different sectors, contexts and phases of a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> humanitarian response.</span></li></ol><h4 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Provision of technical support for disability inclusion in humanitarian action</span></h4><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As the positive awareness among humanitarian actors of the needs of persons with disabilities has grown, so too has the demand for technical support to translate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">guidelines into actions in their specific programs. WRC has been responding to reques</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ts for technical support to UNHCR country operations and other humanitarian organizations which are operational in the field. To date, however, there is a gap in operational agencies with the expertise and capacity to respond in a timely manner to requests</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from humanitarian actors for more detailed and intensive technical support on disability inclusion in specific sectors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at field levels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This is particularly the case in sectors where we still lack detailed guidance and examples of how to operationalize </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">clusion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with persons with different types of disabilities, such as the GBV and child protection sectors.</span></li></ol><h4 style="font-weight:normal; margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Engaging with host country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> DPOs</span></h4><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite many host countries having ratified the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CRPD, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refugees and displaced persons with disabilities are often exclud</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed from CRPD implementation and monitoring processes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Refugees and displaced persons with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rarely have contact with host country DPOs, and most agencies working with them require greater awareness of the CRPD and its processes. While some posit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ive progress has been made with respect to DPO engagement in emergencies and natural disasters, they have limited involvement with refugee or asylum seeker populations, and lack information about the situation of refugees with disabilities in their countri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The WRC has sought to bridge this gap by engaging the disability movement both at national and international levels in our work. Host country DPOs have participated in consultations and workshops in New Delhi, Bangladesh, Uganda and Nepal, and in some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cases are now actively including refugee issues in their work. We have also sought to increase dialogue on the issue within regional and international forums, such as the Civil Society Forum at the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">5th Conference of State Parties to the CRPD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; and have cond</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ucted awareness raising activities in partnership with different DPO networks. We hope through this work, refugees and displaced persons with disabilities will increasingly be included in national policies and programs, and have their rights are represente</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d in CRPD monitoring mechanisms.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Recommendations</span></h2><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The WRC makes the following recommendations for action by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and other actors.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Advance understanding of ‘vulnerability’ in the humanitarian sector</span></h3><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WRC commends</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the UK Government for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recent financial commitment to the Syrian refugee response in Jordan, which will focus on providing much needed assistance for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">those individuals classified as ‘vulnerable’, including meeting some of the specific health-related needs of persons with disabil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ities.</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[12]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WRC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recommend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that such support should be complemented by longer-term commitments to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strengthen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">understand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing and response to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> vulnerability factors in crisis-affected populations, rather than categories of vul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nerable groups, which has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> limi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in reaching the most at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">risk in different</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> phases of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a humanitarian crisis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Actions towards this recommendation may include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">supporting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">systematic reviews of available l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iterature; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">conducting evaluations o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prioritized and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">targeted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> including the a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dvantages and disadvantages of diffe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rent methodologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> employed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in a variety of humanitarian </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contexts;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and finally promoting shari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng and learning about these different methodologies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">humanitarian sector.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Advocate for globally endorsed evide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">nce-based guidelines on disability inclusion within the humanitarian system</span></h3><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Institutionalization of disability inclusion as a cross cutting issue in the humanitarian sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">further advanced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by having globally endorsed evidence-based guidelines at interagency levels. This recommendation could be implemented </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through the coordinated and systematic evaluation of existing strategies and guidelines, collation and development of agreed standards, an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d targeted advocacy to primary interagency coordination mechanisms. With globally endorsed strategies and approaches, plans for capacity development and human resourcing can be established and supported within humanitarian assistance structures, capacitati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng a wider range of sectors and agencies than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">currently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> being achieved.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Fund technical support on disability inclusion in humanitarian action</span></h3><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> absence of institutionalized approaches to disability inclusion across the humanitarian assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> system, there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">still </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a need to meet the increasing demand from humanitarian actors for more intensive and tailored</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> technical support in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> different contexts, programs and phases of a crisi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WRC recommends that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support agencies with tech</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nical expertise in disability inclusion in humanitarian action to expand their human resource capacity in this field through building, training and mentoring a cadre of staff available for deployment to humanitarian contexts to work with protection and oth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er sector actors in the field.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Integrate crisis and conflict issues into disability inclusive development partnerships</span></h3><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:2.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finally, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WRC commends the UK Government for its commitment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability inclusion in their development programs – including urging </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partner governments to deliver on commitments under the CRPD, and supporting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DPOs in developing countries to advocate for the rights of p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ersons with disabilities through long-term commitments to the Disability Rights Fund.</span><a name="_ednref13"></a><a href="#_edn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The universality of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CRPD tex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t means that states are obliged to promote, protect and ensure the rights of all persons with disabilities within their territory – including those who have been displaced across a border.</span><a name="_ednref14"></a><a href="#_edn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s such, the WRC recommends that the UK Government advocate for gr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eater consideration of issues relating to crisis and conflict in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their development partnerships, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">engaging both partner governments and the disability movement in dialogue abou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t promoting human rights for those who may be most </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">marginalized </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability community – wom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en, children and youth displaced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by crisis and conflict – and in turn strengthening the linkages between both development and humanitarian programming.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Contact:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Emma Pearce</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Senior Program Officer – Disability</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Women’s Refugee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Commission</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><a href="mailto:Emmap@wrcommission.org"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Emmap@wrcommission.org</span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-top-color:#622423; 